basicQuestions.answerText:
Most cases of mastocytosis are caused by a change (known as variation or&nbsp;<a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/primer/mutationsanddisorders/genemutation">mutation</a>) in the&nbsp;<a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/KIT"><em>KIT</em></a>&nbsp;<a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/primer/basics/gene">gene</a>. This gene provides instructions to the body to make a protein that helps control many important cellular processes such as cell growth and division, survival, and movement. This protein is also important for the development of certain types of cells, including&nbsp;<a href="https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/articles/mastocytosis">mast cells</a>. Mast cells are cells of the&nbsp;<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/immunesystem.html">immune system</a>&nbsp;that protect the body against infections and produce an&nbsp;<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/000821.htm">inflammatory response</a>&nbsp;when it senses that the body is being attacked.[8372]&nbsp;<br />
<br />
Mutations in the&nbsp;<em>KIT</em>&nbsp;gene can lead to an overproduction of mast cells. In mastocytosis, mast cells accumulate in the skin and/or internal organs, leading to the many signs and symptoms of the disease.[8371]&nbsp;

